abstract: He’s a bad show, but it’s not low-flow.
snippet: He’s a bad show, but it’s not low-flow.
lead_paragraph: We’re now officially trudging through the new year. (And good luck on that healthier-living resolution.) This is when we adjust to the fact that nothing has changed. You weren’t allowed to toss Donald Trump out with the old. Although it would have been nice if he’d at least have stayed quiet until all of the Christmas trees were down.

abstract: Mr. Buttigieg, who appears in strong position in Iowa with a month until the caucuses, continues to show fund-raising strength.
snippet: Mr. Buttigieg, who appears in strong position in Iowa with a month until the caucuses, continues to show fund-raising strength.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Pete Buttigieg raised more than $24.7 million in the fourth quarter of 2019, his presidential campaign said on Wednesday, another strong showing that leaves him well positioned to finance a large campaign operation as primary voting approaches.

headline_main: Pete Buttigieg’s Campaign Says It Raised $24.7 Million in the Fourth Quarter
headline_print_headline: Buttigieg Shows Fund-Raising Strength With a $24.7 Million Quarter

abstract: There are signs her campaign is seeking to calm fears about her health care proposal, including having small meetings with rural Iowa voters to explain her financing and transition plans.
snippet: There are signs her campaign is seeking to calm fears about her health care proposal, including having small meetings with rural Iowa voters to explain her financing and transition plans.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — In warm-up remarks introducing Senator Elizabeth Warren at campaign rallies, young volunteers often say they are supporting her because of her plan to transform the health care system through a single-payer “Medicare for all” program. It happened in Des Moines on Saturday and Oklahoma City last week, and in western Iowa cities like Clarinda and Council Bluffs on Sunday.

headline_main: Elizabeth Warren Isn’t Talking Much About ‘Medicare for All’ Anymore
headline_print_headline: Warren Keeps Medicare Plan At a Distance

abstract: Elizabeth Warren delivered a major speech exactly a year after she entered the presidential race, restating her case against corruption while projecting optimism heading into 2020.
snippet: Elizabeth Warren delivered a major speech exactly a year after she entered the presidential race, restating her case against corruption while projecting optimism heading into 2020.
lead_paragraph: BOSTON — Marking a year since she began her campaign for president and seeking to frame the final five-week sprint to Iowa where much of her candidacy hinges, Senator Elizabeth Warren urged her supporters to “imagine that something better lies on the other side of the chaos and ugliness of the last three years” in a major speech on Tuesday.

headline_main: Warren Urges Democrats to ‘Imagine’ a Better America (and Her as President)
headline_print_headline: Looking for Momentum, Warren Delivers Message of Optimism

abstract: This year saw 13 Democratic candidates and one Republican drop out. Our photographers captured them on the campaign trail. As 2019 ends, here’s a look back.
snippet: This year saw 13 Democratic candidates and one Republican drop out. Our photographers captured them on the campaign trail. As 2019 ends, here’s a look back.
lead_paragraph: Some candidates were in for just a few months; others for almost the entire year. One left the race before most others even entered it. And now, at the end of 2019, a historically large field of presidential contenders has shrunk from more than two dozen to a slightly more manageable group of 18.

headline_main: The Presidential Class of 2019: Remembering the 14 Who Moved On

abstract: How a series of turning points in mid-October explains the state of the race today and can serve as a cheat sheet for the casual 2020 primary observer.
snippet: How a series of turning points in mid-October explains the state of the race today and can serve as a cheat sheet for the casual 2020 primary observer.
lead_paragraph: Month after month, former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. led national polls in the Democratic presidential primary race. But in early October, someone else seemed to crack the code. Lifted by her bevy of policy plans and grass-roots momentum, Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts joined Mr. Biden in a statistical tie atop the party’s large field of candidates.

abstract: An early look at fourth-quarter fund-raising shows Joseph R. Biden Jr. bouncing back, Elizabeth Warren lagging her previous benchmark and Bernie Sanders continuing to haul in cash.
snippet: An early look at fourth-quarter fund-raising shows Joseph R. Biden Jr. bouncing back, Elizabeth Warren lagging her previous benchmark and Bernie Sanders continuing to haul in cash.
lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren’s slip in the 2020 primary polls has been accompanied by a dip in donations, with her campaign setting a rare public goal: aiming to raise $20 million for the fourth quarter of 2019 ending Tuesday, or about 20 percent less than what she raised in the previous three-month period.
